00:12:19.560 --> 00:12:23.940
The larger research asks the
question, how did the world

00:12:23.940 --> 00:12:27.550
of states emerge from a
former world of empires?

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:30.750
After all, the existence
of states today is a fact

00:12:30.750 --> 00:12:32.050
that we take for granted.

00:12:32.050 --> 00:12:34.860
The unprecedented growth of--

00:12:34.860 --> 00:12:38.730
in the umber of states since the
mid 20th century has largely been a

00:12:38.730 --> 00:12:43.270 position:56%
product of decolonization in Africa,
in Asia, but forms of sovereignty

00:12:43.270 --> 00:12:45.660
which are recognizably
modern have existed

00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:48.530
since at least late 18th century.

00:12:48.530 --> 00:12:51.270
And the founding of this
country in particular illuminates

00:12:51.270 --> 00:12:53.840
at least one significant
point about the creation

00:12:53.840 --> 00:12:59.530 position:56%
of states namely their desire for
independence or domestic sovereignty

00:12:59.530 --> 00:13:03.450
but also commitment to
interdependence in their relations

00:13:03.450 --> 00:13:07.870
with other states, what I call
international sovereignty.

00:13:07.870 --> 00:13:09.170
While writing the genealogy

00:13:09.170 --> 00:13:12.090
of the modern statehood can
be approached variously,

00:13:12.090 --> 00:13:14.510
the one story I have chosen
to pursue is the birth

00:13:14.510 --> 00:13:18.410
of the United States in late
18th and early 19th century.

00:13:18.410 --> 00:13:22.220
Such a pursuit is not entirely
arbitrary tracing the origin

00:13:22.220 --> 00:13:27.470
of the state back to British North
America in the 1770s allows us

00:13:27.470 --> 00:13:31.140
to situate the idea of sovereignty
not only in its domestic,

00:13:31.140 --> 00:13:33.340
but especially in its
international context.

00:13:33.340 --> 00:13:35.740
And I'll make that more
clear as I move along.

00:13:35.740 --> 00:13:39.920
That context can be found in what
was called at that time the law

00:13:39.920 --> 00:13:43.060
of nature and nations
and that, which is coming

00:13:43.060 --> 00:13:45.000
to be called international law.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.910
And some of you may know that
the term international law was

00:13:47.910 --> 00:13:52.980
in fact coined by Jeremy Bentham in
1786 to designate a different way

00:13:52.980 --> 00:13:55.480
of thinking about the
Law of Nations.

00:13:55.480 --> 00:13:57.700
Such a law was partially normative

00:13:57.700 --> 00:14:00.390
for it prescribed how
states ought to behave.

00:14:00.390 --> 00:14:04.450
And it was partly conventional
for it was based in convention

00:14:04.450 --> 00:14:08.590
and described the established
practices among states.

00:14:08.590 --> 00:14:12.430
In my remarks today, I locate
the rising United States

00:14:12.430 --> 00:14:17.710
in late 18th century in these two
conceptions of international law,

00:14:17.710 --> 00:14:20.250
the normative and the conventional.

00:14:20.250 --> 00:14:23.400
And I argue that the American
revolutionaries were making claims

00:14:23.400 --> 00:14:27.690
not only for independence from
Britain, but also if not primarily

00:14:27.690 --> 00:14:31.250
for interdependence
among other states.

00:14:31.250 --> 00:14:34.960
Their ultimate goal was not merely
domestic autonomy, but above all,

00:14:34.960 --> 00:14:39.180
external recognition by
other states beyond Britain.

00:14:39.180 --> 00:14:43.200
They clearly understood that
independence was their ticket

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:47.340
for admission into the
international community of states,

00:14:47.340 --> 00:14:49.580
but the American revolutionaries
would have hardly been able

00:14:49.580 --> 00:14:52.120
to accomplish their global
reach had it not been

00:14:52.120 --> 00:14:55.480
for a Swiss political thinker
by the name of Emer Vattel,

00:14:55.480 --> 00:14:58.500
the name I will be
mentioning in my discussion.

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:04.020
So he is? Born in 1714 in the
Swiss principality of Neuchatel,

00:15:04.020 --> 00:15:06.240
Vattel came from a
privilege background.

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:09.080
His father was a high ranking
clergyman while his mother was the

00:15:09.080 --> 00:15:11.670
daughter of the treasure
of Prussian King.

00:15:11.670 --> 00:15:15.460
His interest in philosophy on his
father's side and taste of politics

00:15:15.460 --> 00:15:19.760
on his mother's side
define his passion for both.

00:15:19.760 --> 00:15:22.140
His main work, the Law
of Nations published

00:15:22.140 --> 00:15:25.140
in 1758 was not envisioned.

00:15:25.140 --> 00:15:26.440
And this is a key point.

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:29.540
It was not envisioned to make an
original contribution it was simply

00:15:29.540 --> 00:15:31.260
intended to popularize the works

00:15:31.260 --> 00:15:35.610
of two German philosophers,
Leibniz and Wolff.

00:15:35.610 --> 00:15:39.540
Both of whom had produced
works on the law of nature.

00:15:39.540 --> 00:15:42.340
Ingenuous as their works were
and can tell that by the length

00:15:42.340 --> 00:15:47.170
of their wigs, they remain largely
inaccessible to wider audience.

00:15:47.170 --> 00:15:50.320
Written in Latin, they were full
of mathematical demonstrations

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:53.400
